        <h2>Schema Markup on an SME Budget</h2>
        <p><strong>Structured data implementation does not require a developer — modern CMS plugins handle the most impactful schema types with a few clicks.</strong> The key is knowing which schema types deliver the highest AEO impact and which can wait.</p>
        <p>For WordPress sites, plugins such as Yoast SEO Premium, Rank Math, and Schema Pro handle FAQPage, HowTo, Article, and LocalBusiness schema through a GUI, eliminating the need to write JSON-LD by hand. For Shopify, apps like JSON-LD for SEO and Smart SEO cover Product and Organisation schemas. For custom-built sites, Google's Structured Data Markup Helper generates valid JSON-LD that you can paste directly into page templates.</p>

        <h3>Priority Schema Types for SMEs</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>FAQPage</strong> — the single most impactful schema type for AEO; marks up every FAQ section for direct-answer extraction.</li>
          <li><strong>LocalBusiness</strong> (or relevant subtype: Plumber, AccountingService, LegalService, etc.) — essential for local answer visibility; feeds Google Business Profile and voice search answers.</li>
          <li><strong>Article / TechArticle</strong> — signals content type and establishes datePublished/dateModified for freshness signals.</li>
          <li><strong>BreadcrumbList</strong> — clarifies site structure; used by Google AI Overviews to contextualise page placement within a topic hierarchy.</li>
          <li><strong>HowTo</strong> — high-impact for process pages ("how to apply for planning permission," "how to change a fuse box"); triggers rich results directly.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Validate every schema implementation with Google's free Rich Results Test before and after deployment. Invalid structured data is counterproductive — it signals technical unreliability to search and AI systems alike.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Local AEO -->
      <section id="local-aeo" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Local AEO for Service Businesses</h2>
        <p><strong>For local service businesses, local AEO is the highest-value subset of answer engine optimisation — voice search queries carry a substantial local-intent component, and AI systems draw heavily on Google Business Profile data to answer them.</strong></p>
        <p>Voice queries such as "what are the best heating engineers near me" and "find a solicitor in [town]" are answered by AI systems that synthesise data from multiple sources: the Google Business Profile, the business website, review platforms, and local citations in directories. Each of these data sources is a local AEO signal.</p>

        <h3>Google Business Profile as an AEO Asset</h3>
        <p>Your Google Business Profile is one of the most underutilised AEO assets in local marketing. The Q&amp;A section of the profile — which allows businesses to pre-populate frequently asked questions — is directly indexed and cited in local AI-generated answers. Populate it with the ten questions you are most commonly asked, with concise, accurate answers. This is equivalent to adding FAQ schema to your website, but for the local knowledge panel.</p>
        <p>The business description field should lead with a clear, keyword-rich statement of what you do and where you serve, using the same inverted-pyramid structure as your website content. Services should be fully listed with descriptions — AI systems use this structured data when answering "does [business name] do X" queries.</p>

        <h3>Local Citation Consistency</h3>
        <p>Inconsistent name, address, and phone number (NAP) data across directories confuses the entity resolution process that AI systems use when generating local answers. Audit your business listings across Google Business Profile, Yelp, Yell, Checkatrade, Trustpilot, and any industry-specific directories. Ensure your trading name, address format, and contact details are identical across all of them.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 7: Tools -->
      <section id="tools" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Free and Low-Cost AEO Tools for SMEs</h2>
          <p><strong>Effective AEO measurement for an SME does not require an enterprise software subscription — a carefully selected set of free and low-cost tools covers the essentials.</strong></p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Google Search Console (Free)</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">The primary tool for tracking featured snippet appearances. Filter the Performance report by "Search type: Web" and look for queries where your impressions are high but click-through is low — these are queries where you appear in an answer box but users do not click through. GSC also surfaces which queries trigger rich results for your schema implementations.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Google's Rich Results Test (Free)</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Validates your structured data implementation and shows exactly which rich result types your schema is eligible for. Run this after every schema addition before publishing. Non-valid schema is invisible to answer engines and wastes implementation effort.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">AlsoAsked (Free tier available)</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Maps the People Also Ask question clusters for any keyword. The free tier provides enough data for an SME to identify the ten to twenty most important PAA questions in their niche and build content to address them directly.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Schema.org Validator (Free)</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">The canonical reference for structured data syntax. Useful for checking custom JSON-LD markup against the official specification before deploying it. Particularly important for less common schema types not covered by CMS plugins.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Semrush or Ahrefs (Paid, ~£100/month)</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Both platforms offer featured snippet tracking at the keyword level, showing whether you or a competitor currently holds a given snippet. For SMEs with a manageable keyword list (under 200 queries), the base plan is sufficient to identify and track the answer positions that matter most to the business.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 8: 90-Day Action Plan -->
      <section id="action-plan" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>A 90-Day AEO Action Plan for SMEs</h2>
        <p><strong>Ninety days of focused AEO effort is enough for most SMEs to establish measurable answer-box presence for their core keywords.</strong> The plan below is structured in three phases, each building on the last.</p>

        <h3>Days 1–30: Foundations</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Set up Google Search Console if not already active. Verify site ownership, submit sitemap, and baseline your current featured snippet appearances using the Search Appearance filter.</li>
          <li>Identify your five most commercially important pages (typically your homepage, main service page, and top-performing blog posts). These are your AEO priority targets.</li>
          <li>For each priority page: rewrite H2s as questions, add a concise definitional opening paragraph, and add a 4–6 question FAQ section at the bottom.</li>
          <li>Implement FAQPage schema on all five priority pages. Validate each with Google's Rich Results Test.</li>
          <li>Fully populate your Google Business Profile: description, Q&amp;A section (10 questions minimum), all service listings with descriptions, and ensure NAP consistency with your website.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Days 31–60: Expansion</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Use AlsoAsked or manual SERP research to identify the twenty most important PAA questions in your category. Map each to an existing page or flag for new content.</li>
          <li>Add dedicated H2/H3 sections and FAQ entries on existing pages for the PAA questions that align with your current content. Do not create thin new pages — enrich existing ones first.</li>
          <li>Add HowTo schema to any process-based pages. Add Article or TechArticle schema to blog posts and guides.</li>
          <li>Deploy a basic llms.txt file in your site root. Include a brief description of your business, your primary expertise areas, and links to your most authoritative pages.</li>
          <li>Check robots.txt to ensure AI crawlers (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot) are not being blocked inadvertently.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Days 61–90: Consolidation and Measurement</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Review GSC data for the first two months. Identify which queries now show rich result impressions and which priority pages have gained featured snippet or PAA appearances.</li>
          <li>For any target queries where a competitor holds the answer position, analyse their content structure. Identify the specific structural advantage (shorter definition, clearer list, more specific data) and implement the improvement.</li>
          <li>Begin creating new content for the PAA questions that had no suitable existing page. Prioritise by search volume and commercial relevance.</li>
          <li>Submit an IndexNow ping and re-submit your sitemap to GSC after significant content updates.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>For specialist support on any phase of this plan, our <a href="/aeo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO services</a> include SME-specific audit and implementation packages designed to deliver maximum impact on a constrained budget.</p>
      </section>

